      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:28-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Heretics are our fellow-creatures; Jesus died for them also, and our office is to win them. If we close our doors and our hearts against them, we lose our opportunity of winning them and harden them in their opposition. There are two thoughts which may well teach us forbearance and humility: (1) The patience of the Lord. A Jewish fable tells how Abraham thrust an aged wayfarer from his tent because he asked no blessing on his food and avowed himself a fire-worshipper. And the Lord said: “I have suffered him these hundred years, although he dishonoured Me; and couldst not thou endure him for one night?” (2) The mystery of the things of God and the blindness of our intellects. “Illi,” says St. Augustine (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Contra Epistolam Manichcæi",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 2), “in vos sæviant, qui neseiunt cum quo labore verum inveniatur, et quam difficile caveantur errores”. This counsel of the Apostle must be read in the light of local circumstances. There was need of caution and discrimination in receiving the itinerant “apostles and prophets” who went from church to church, lest they should prove “false apostles” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ψευδαπόστολοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and “false prophets” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ψευδοπροφῆται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Didache",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xi.–xii., where the test is given: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὐ πᾶς ὁ λαλῶν ἐν πνεύματι προφήτης ἐστίν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀλλʼ ἐὰν ἔχῃ τοὺς τπρόπους Κυρίου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is not until the second century that there is any appearance of buildings set apart for worship. The primitive ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκκλησίαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " met in private houses (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
